query:
title: How to change type of properties object with new version?

question: We have the following proxy resource definition:
```
@parentResource(HealthModel)
model DiscoveryRule is ProxyResource<DiscoveryRuleProperties> {
  @doc("Name of the discovery rule. Must be unique within a health model.")
  @key("discoveryRuleName")
  @segment("discoveryrules")
  @path
  name: discoveryRuleName;
}

@doc("Discovery rule properties")
model DiscoveryRuleProperties {
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  @doc("The status of the last operation.")
  provisioningState?: HealthModelProvisioningState;

 ....
}
```
Now, with the next API version we need to change the Properties to have a discriminator. As far as I can tell, there is no was to add the @disriminator decorator on the existing one and say "added in version xyz".
So I guess, we would need a whole new properties object (and mark the previous one with @removed:
```

@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
@doc("Discovery rule properties")
@discriminator("discoveryRuleKind")
model DiscoveryRulePropertiesV2 {
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  @doc("The status of the last operation.")
  provisioningState?: HealthModelProvisioningState;

  @doc("Kind of the discovery rule")
  discoveryRuleKind: DiscoveryRuleKind;
...
}
```
Question is: How to update the DiscoveryRule proxy resource to use the new properties object with the new version?

ground_truth:
A couple of things:
No, you cannot version decorator application
Polymorphic resources (including polymorphic rp-specific property bags) are discouraged - you are generally much better off making one of the properties in the property bag polymorphic.
If you need to do this, you have two choices
Replace the resource and all its operations with a new set
Use an augment decorator `@typeChangedFrom` to change the properties property, like this.  In this option, you might also need to version your Update operation, depending on whether it references the property type.
```
/** A ContosoProviderHub resource */
model Employee is TrackedResource<EmployeePropertiesV2> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<Employee>;
}

/** Employee properties */
@removed(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
model EmployeeProperties {
  /** Age of employee */
  age?: int32;

  /** City of employee */
  city?: string;

  /** Profile of employee */
  @encode("base64url")
  profile?: bytes;

  /** The status of the last operation. */
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  provisioningState?: ProvisioningState;
}

@added(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
union EmployeeKind {
  Kind1: "kind1",
  Kind2: "kind2",
  string,
}

@added(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
@discriminator("kind")
model EmployeePropertiesV2 {
  kind: EmployeeKind;
}

@added(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
model EmplProp1 extends EmployeePropertiesV2 {
  kind: EmployeeKind.Kind1;
}

@added(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
model EmplProp2 extends EmployeePropertiesV2 {
  kind: EmployeeKind.Kind2;
}

@@typeChangedFrom(Employee.properties,
  Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`,
  EmployeeProperties
);
```

According to Azure ARM and REST API guidelines, properties that are patchable (i.e., those included in PATCH operations, typically with Lifecycle.Update visibility) should NOT have default values in the PATCH request schema. This is to ensure that PATCH only updates explicitly provided fields and does not unintentionally overwrite values with defaults.
However, if a property has a default value in the service (i.e., the service will assign a value if none is provided), the API specification (OpenAPI/TypeSpec) should document that default value for PUT/POST operations and in the resource schema, so that clients know what value will be used if they omit the property. 
In TypeSpec, you can set a default value for a property using the `=` syntax, e.g.:

```
model Example {
  value?: int32 = 42;
}
```

This will emit a `default` field in the OpenAPI schema for PUT/POST (create/update) operations and in the resource definition. But for PATCH operations, you must ensure that the PATCH schema does NOT include default values for patchable properties. The recommended approach is to use a separate PATCH model or a transformation (such as `Update<T>`) that omits defaults for PATCH requests.
For example, for a resource property with Lifecycle.Create, Lifecycle.Update, and Lifecycle.Read visibility:

```
model ResourceProperties {
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Create, Lifecycle.Update, Lifecycle.Read)
  myField?: int32 = 42; // Default value for PUT/POST, but NOT for PATCH
}

// PATCH model should omit default:
model ResourcePropertiesPatch is Update<ResourceProperties>;
```

Summary:
You CAN set a default value for a property with Lifecycle.Create/Update/Read, but the PATCH schema must NOT include the default value.
The OpenAPI spec should show the default value for PUT/POST and resource schemas if the service assigns one.
For PATCH, use a model or transformation that omits defaults, complying with ARM guidelines.

query:
title: Versioning a default

question: Hello,
My team has a property called enableRbacAuthorization. This property has always been set to false, but will however change with the introduction of a new API version. Older API versions will still maintain the old default, how can I go about versioning this? Below is what I would assume to be the correct approach, but I see VS Code complaining that there is a duplicate property

```
enableRbacAuthorization?: boolean = false;
@added(KeyVault.Versions.`2026-02-01`)
enableRbacAuthorization?: boolean = true;
```

ground_truth:
You're running into a known limitation in TypeSpec: there is currently no versioning decorator for changing a property's default value directly. If you try to declare two properties with the same name (even with @added), TypeSpec will flag this as a duplicate property.
To model a versioned default value (e.g., enableRbacAuthorization is false in older versions, and true in 2026-02-01 and later), you need to use the 'remove/rename dance' workaround. That is, you:
1.Remove the original property in the new version and rename it for history.
2.Add a new property (with the same name) in the new version, but with the new default value.
Here's how you do it in TypeSpec:

```
model KeyVaultProperties {
  // The original property for old versions
  @removed(KeyVault.Versions.`2026-02-01`)
  @renamedFrom(KeyVault.Versions.`2026-02-01`, "enableRbacAuthorization")
  enableRbacAuthorizationOld?: boolean = false;

  // The new property for 2026-02-01 and later
  @added(KeyVault.Versions.`2026-02-01`)
  enableRbacAuthorization?: boolean = true;
}
```

This approach ensures:
In all versions before 2026-02-01, the property is present with default false.
In 2026-02-01 and later, the property is present with default true.

