title: Query on Patch Replace or append to property

question: On a patch of resource , if a paticular property is being patched , we want to append the value to the list rather than replace. Is that possible to do in swagger. It is an rpaas based RP. Currently our api is defined like below

  @summary("Creates or updates an Application resource synchronously.")
  createOrUpdate is ArmResourceCreateOrReplaceSync<Application>;

  @summary("Updates an Application resource synchronously.")
  update is ArmResourcePatchSync<Application, ApplicationProperties>;

ground_truth:
It is strongly recommended that property names and other types that become identifiers in generated SDKs not contain characters like underscore, because these are not easily representable as identifiers in all languages and/or violate the preferred coding style in some languages.  If you can, it is best to not use characters outside the standard set.  

If there is some compelling business reason not to use these characters, then it's possible to suppress the violation in typespec using an inline suppression, i.e.:

```
model Example {
  #suppress "@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core/casing-style" "<good-business-justification-here>
  priorityValue8021Action_Cluster: string;
}
```

query:
title: Updating description for property updates across all api versions instead of just one.

question: I am trying to introduce new filters in my list API. The older api version already supported filtering on some properties and we are now introducing a couple of new properties to filter on. When I make that update in the tsp it updates in the older versions as well. 
This file for example: 
```diff
namespace Microsoft.Advisor;

/**
 * Update the tracked properties of a Recommendation.
 */
#suppress "@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core/response-schema-problem" "FIXME: Update justification, follow aka.ms/tsp/conversion-fix for details"

+@added(Versions.v2025_05_01_preview)
+@removed(Versions.v2026_02_01_preview)
@patch(#{
  implicitOptionality: false
})
patch is ArmCustomPatchSync<
  ResourceRecommendationBase,

@@ -55,7 +58,7 @@ interface ResourceRecommendationBases {
  BaseParameters = Azure.ResourceManager.Foundations.SubscriptionBaseParameters,
  Parameters = {
    /**
-     * The filter to apply to the recommendations.<br>Filter can be applied to properties ['ResourceId', 'ResourceGroup', 'RecommendationTypeGuid',
-     * '[Category](#category)'] with operators ['eq', 'and', 'or'].<br>Example:<br> $filter=Category eq 'Cost' and ResourceGroup eq 'MyResourceGroup'
     */
+    * The filter to apply to the recommendations.<br>Filter can be applied to properties ['ResourceId', 'ResourceGroup', 'RecommendationTypeGuid',
+    * '[Category](#category)', '[State](#state)'] with operators ['eq', 'and', 'or'].<br>Example:<br> $filter=Category eq 'Cost' and ResourceGroup eq
+    * 'MyResourceGroup' and State eq 'New'. Please note that State is available as a filter from API Version 2026-02-01-preview.
     */
    @query("$filter")
    $filter?: string;

```
Since the update is only in the comment - it also updates the description in the older API versions.

Similarly - we are introducing a new property in the response contract called lastRefreshed which will now hold the value for what used to be lastUpdated and the description and value of lastUpdated in our new API version is changing: 
```

/**
 * The most recent time that Advisor checked the validity of the recommendation.
 */
 // FIXME: (utcDateTime) Please double check that this is the correct type for your scenario.

@added(Versions.v2026_02_01_preview)
lastRefreshed?: utcDateTime;

/**
 * The most recent time that Advisor recommendation was updated.
 */
lastUpdated?: utcDateTime;
```
How can i version the description to make sure the change happens only for the new api version?

ground_truth:
Unfortunately, you can't version a decorator application, so the best thing is generally to make this documentation change in a way that describes when the property is available (as you have).  You will want to be sure that it's really the case that this new filter is only available in the newest versions.
The property change you mention seems like a breaking change in disguise.  Why are you replacing a property with another property with a very similar description and the same type?  This feels kind of difficult to decipher for customers.

It's possible to do this with a rename/remove/added, pairing of properties as in this playground .  You can see the idea described in the versioning documentation here: [Versioning | TypeSpec Azure](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/docs/howtos/arm/versioning/#adding-decoration-to-an-existing-type)

You could do this with the filter parameter as well.

Use a `@renamedFrom` / `@removed` / `@added` pairing so the new description applies only from the new version:

```typespec
model EmployeeProperties {
  /** old property with an old description */
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  @renamedFrom(Versions.`2026-03-01-preview`, "oldProperty")
  @removed(Versions.`2026-03-01-preview`)
  oldOldProperty: string;

  /** Old property with a new description */
  @added(Versions.`2026-03-01-preview`)
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  oldProperty: string;

  /** new property with a new description */
  @added(Versions.`2026-03-01-preview`)
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  newProperty: string;
}
```

It is actually possible to model this with discriminators using openapi2 + autorest extensions, the chief issue with OpenAPi2 in this scenario is that the discriminator value has to match the schema name for each leaf schema.  Using x-ms-discriminator-value allows you to express this pattern like this
```
@discriminator("type")
model AorB {
  type: AOrBType;
}

enum AOrBType {
  A: "a",
  B: "b",
}

model A extends AorB {
  type: AOrBType.A;
}

model B extends AorB {
  type: AOrBType.B;
}

```

Although, this is clearer (but not supported by most tsp client generators)

```
@discriminated(#{ envelope: "none", discriminatorPropertyName: "type" })
union Foo {
  a: FooA,
  b: FooB,
}

model FooA {}

model FooB {}
```

Of course, you will actually need to model this in TypeSpec.

The error is happening because, after the refactor, your EKM operations are being included in the `@versioned` Key Vault Administration service without being gated to only the new API version. When TypeSpec emits OpenAPI for older versions, it now also emits the `/ekm*` paths, so oad sees those as AddedPath changes in existing GA/preview versions.
To fix this you need to: (1) make EKM operations visible only starting at the new 2026‑01‑01‑preview version via versioning decorators, and (2) ensure your emit/readme only produces OpenAPI for that new version when you add those operations. Concretely:
1.In your Administration TypeSpec, make sure you have a proper Versions enum that includes the new preview as the latest entry:
```
import "@typespec/versioning";
using TypeSpec.Versioning;

@versioned(KeyVault.Administration.Versions)
@service
namespace KeyVault.Administration;

enum Versions {
  // existing versions in order
  v2025_07_01: "2025-07-01",
  v7_5: "7.5",
  v7_6: "7.6",
  v2025_06_01_preview: "2025-06-01-preview",
  // new preview LAST so it becomes default
  v2026_01_01_preview: "2026-01-01-preview",
}
```
2.Gate every new EKM type and operation with `@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)` so they only exist in that version and later:
```
@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
@route("/ekm")
op GetEkmConfiguration(...): ...;

@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
@route("/ekm/certificate")
op RotateEkmCertificate(...): ...;

@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
@route("/ekm/check")
op CheckEkmStatus(...): ...;

@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
@route("/ekm/create")
op CreateEkmConfiguration(...): ...;

@added(Versions.v2026_01_01_preview)
model EkmConfiguration { ... }
```
If you defined EKM operations inside an interface, add `@added` at the member level (or on the interface if it is entirely new for 2026‑01‑01‑preview and referenced only there).
3.Re‑run `tsp compile` and regenerate OpenAPI. For older versions (`7.5`, `7.6`, `2025‑07‑01`, `2025‑06‑01‑preview`), the emitter will no longer include `/ekm*` paths, so `administration.json` for those versions will match `main` and 1038 (AddedPath) will clear. Only the 2026‑01‑01‑preview `administration.json` will contain the new EKM routes, which is expected and non‑breaking because it’s a new API version.
If, for some reason, you are using the AutoRest emitter separately, do not use the `version` option to emit older OpenAPI versions from a spec that already contains the new 2026‑01‑01‑preview surface; instead, emit each OpenAPI version from the versioned TypeSpec once, relying on the `@added` decorators to control which operations appear per version.
This keeps your EKM additions scoped to the new preview version and aligns with the non‑breaking versioning rules.

query:
title: MadeOptional decorator

question: Hi team, I wanted to ask if it is possible to add a @madeOptional decorator + a version number to a previously required field?
For example:
in v1
```
model Request {
resources: string
}
```
Can I then have v2 like
```
model Request {
@madeOptional(Versions.v2)
resources: string
}
```

ground_truth:
Yes. That is exactly what @madeOptional is for.
In your case you would write the model once (representing the latest state) and decorate the property with @madeOptional for the version where it became optional:
```
using TypeSpec.Versioning;

enum Versions {
  v1,
  v2,
}

model Request {
  @madeOptional(Versions.v2)
  resources?: string;
}
```
Resulting behavior:
- v1: `resources` is required
- v2 and later: `resources` is optional

Note: Per Azure guidelines, making a response property optional is considered a breaking change unless paired with a default, so this may need review depending on where `resources` is used.

query:
title: Adding optional request body to existing operation that was previously void?

question: Hi, my team's service has an existing operation managedApplyMaintenanceWindow_Post

[azure-rest-api-specs/specification/servicefabricmanagedclusters/resource-manager/Microsoft.ServiceF…](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/blob/main/specification/servicefabricmanagedclusters/resource-manager/Microsoft.ServiceFabric/ServiceFabricManagedClusters/stable/2026-02-01/servicefabricmanagedclusters.json) 

It currently doesn't have any body parameters. We'd like to add an optional body parameter so the user can provide more inputs. Is this allowed? If so, what is the recommended way to change our typespec for this? The current body below

```
#suppress "@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core/no-openapi" "Backwards compatibility with non-standard operation id"
  @action("applyMaintenanceWindow")
  @operationId("managedApplyMaintenanceWindow_Post")
  post is ArmResourceActionSync<ManagedCluster, void, OkResponse>;
```

ground_truth:
There is an `OptionalRequestBody` parameter you can use to add an optional request  body, here is a sample, adding this in a new api-version.

```
@armResourceOperations
interface Employees {
  get is ArmResourceRead<Employee>;
  createOrUpdate is ArmResourceCreateOrReplaceAsync<Employee>;
  update is ArmCustomPatchSync<Employee, EmployeeUpdate>;
  delete is ArmResourceDeleteWithoutOkAsync<Employee>;
  listByResourceGroup is ArmResourceListByParent<Employee>;
  listBySubscription is ArmListBySubscription<Employee>;

  /** A sample resource action that move employee to different location */
  @sharedRoute
  @renamedFrom(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`, "move")
  @removed(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
  moveOld is ArmResourceActionSync<Employee, void, MoveResponse>;

  @sharedRoute
  @added(Versions.`2025-10-01-preview`)
  move is ArmResourceActionSync<
    Employee,
    MoveRequest,
    MoveResponse,
    OptionalRequestBody = true
  >;

  /** A sample HEAD operation to check resource existence */
  checkExistence is ArmResourceCheckExistence<Employee>;
}
```

Use a normal child resource modeled with `@parentResource` and mark it as a singleton with `@Azure.ResourceManager.singleton`.
Minimal pattern:
```
using Azure.ResourceManager;

// Parent tracked resource
model ParentResource is TrackedResource<ParentProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<ParentResource>;
}

model ParentProperties {
  // parent properties here
}

// Singleton child resource
@parentResource(ParentResource)
@singleton("default")  // or omit parameter to use "default"
model ChildSingletonResource is ProxyResource<ChildSingletonProperties> {
  @segment("childSingletons")
  @key("childName")
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  @path
  name: string; // value is always "default" in the URI
}

model ChildSingletonProperties {
  // singleton child properties here
}

@armResourceOperations
interface ChildSingletons {
  // standard child-resource operations; create will be PUT .../childSingletons/default
  get is ArmResourceRead<ChildSingletonResource>;
  createOrUpdate is ArmResourceCreateOrReplaceAsync<ChildSingletonResource>;
  delete is ArmResourceDeleteSync<ChildSingletonResource>;
  listByParent is ArmResourceListByParent<ChildSingletonResource>;
}
```
This generates a path like:
`/subscriptions/{subId}/resourceGroups/{rg}/providers/{RP}/parentResources/{parentName}/childSingletons/default`
with the `name` fixed to `default` (or your chosen literal), which is the ARM‑compliant singleton child resource pattern.

You can’t ask the TypeSpec/OpenAPI emitters to set x-ms-pageable.nextLinkName: null. Instead, model the future‑proof, standards‑compliant pattern now by adding an optional nextLink and using normal paging decorators.
Recommended pattern (ARM & data‑plane aligned):
1.Define the response model with optional nextLink and page items:
```
model ItemList {
  @pageItems
  value: Item[];
  @nextLink
  nextLink?: string;  // or url if your service will return a valid URI
}
```
2.Mark the operation as a list:
```
@list
@get
op listItems(...): ItemList;
```
This will emit:
```
"x-ms-pageable": {
  "nextLinkName": "nextLink"
}
```
Today your service simply doesn’t return nextLink (or returns it only when you actually support multiple pages). Because nextLink is optional, this is not a breaking change and matches the guidance: clients handle “no next page” when the nextLink field is absent.
If you absolutely must have no x-ms-pageable until the service is truly paged, define your list operation without @list and without @pageItems/@nextLink for now and add them later when you introduce paging. There is no supported way in TypeSpec to emit x-ms-pageable with nextLinkName: null as a staging step.
One thing to add, Changing an operation from non-pageable to pageable is a breaking change for most SDKs.  For that reason, if you know these list APIs are going to be pageable in the future (and all list APIs should be)  then you should model them as pageable now, and it won't be a breaking change when the service starts returning extra pages.
This means that not including @list is not something you should consider - in that case you have modeled an optional nextLink in the response, but the resulting SDK will show a non-pageable API and will require a breaking change once additional pages are returned.

For TypeSpec‑based Azure SDK generation, constructor visibility (public vs. internal) is not controlled by a generic flag in tspconfig.yaml; it is driven by the accessibility of the types and members as calculated by the Azure client generator core.
The key control is the @Azure.ClientGenerator.Core.access decorator (and the Access enum) in your TypeSpec:
```
import "@azure-tools/typespec-client-generator-core";
using Azure.ClientGenerator.Core;

// Internal model → SDK type is internal / not exposed
@access(Access.internal)
model InternalModel {
  value: string;
}

// Public model → SDK type is public
@access(Access.public)
model PublicModel {
  value: string;
}

// Access can also be applied at operation / namespace level and propagates to models
@route("/items")
@access(Access.internal)
op getInternalItem(): InternalModel;
```
The client generator core computes per‑type and per‑property accessibility (public vs. internal). Language emitters (C#, Java, Python, TS, Go) then map that accessibility to language‑specific constructs – including whether constructors and members are public or internal/hidden. There is no separate "constructor‑visibility" switch; you control it by marking models/operations/namespaces as Access.public or Access.internal and letting the access propagation rules determine what becomes internal in the SDK.
If you have a concrete language/emitter (e.g., C# mgmt vs. C# data‑plane) and a specific case where a constructor isn’t coming out with the visibility you expect, share the TypeSpec snippet and I can show the exact @access layout needed.

query:
title: Service-side default not carried over to emitted Python SDK

question: Here is an example TypeSpec operation we have for the Foundry service:
```
@delete
  @route("/agents/{agent_name}/versions/{agent_version}")
  deleteAgentVersion is FoundryDataPlaneOperation<
    {
      @path agent_name: string;
      @path agent_version: string;
      @query force?: boolean = false;
    },
    DeleteAgentVersionResponse
  >;
```
Note the service side default value "false" listed for "force".

It gets emitted as this Python method:
```
   def delete_agent_version(
        self, agent_name: str, agent_version: str, *, force: Optional[bool] = None, **kwargs: Any
    ) -> _models.DeleteAgentVersionResponse:
```
Note the "None" is now shown as the default value for "force". This hides the service-side default value. the SDK user does not know what the service side default is, if they do not provide this keyword argument. We need to resort to doc string to explicitly re-state the service side default, even though it's already specified in the TypeSpec.

Why is the emitter designed this way?

Is there a way to change the Python emitter to have  force: Optional[bool] = false in the emitted Python code, to clearly show the default when this keyword is not provided?
